SIMPLE: disorient
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Disorient
<hw>Dis*o"ri*ent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
turn away from the east; to confuse as to which way is east; to cause to
lose one's bearings.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Bp.
Warburton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>to cause (a person) to lose one's sense of
direction; to cause to lose one's bearings or way; <as>as, the tourist
was <ex>disoriented</ex> by the winding and narrow
streets</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Psychiatry)</fld> <def>to cause one to lose one's
sense of time or place, or of one's own personal identity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>to confuse (a person) by changing or removing
something which has served as a standard or guide to action; <as>as,
workers were rendered unemployed and <ex>disoriented</ex> by the rapid
changes in the markets</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Disorientate</ent>⟦br⟧
